#### Related work

Our study and results build on several different lines of work, and we draw some parallels in what follows.

**Analysis of attention-based models.** Given the widespread use of Transformers in natural language processing, there has been a surge of interest in understanding the function and significance of attention layers within these models. In , the authors show that when treated as discrete-time systems with additional dense layers and multiple heads appended to the core attention mechanism, Transformers exhibit the universal approximation property. In , the authors present, to the best of our knowledge, the first interacting particle systems perspective on Transformers. They then leverage the similarities between Transformers (with an additional feed-forward layer compared to (1)) and convection-diffusion equations to slightly improve the performance of Transformers by employing a Strang-Marchuk splitting scheme for time discretization. In , the authors interpret system (1) as the characteristics of a continuity equation. Drawing on the similarities between (1) and Sinkhorn iterations, they propose a novel architecture dubbed _Sinkformer_, which possesses the desirable property of being a Wasserstein gradient flow.

